Part I - (The PISA 2012 Dataset)¶

- Shalom Karunwi¶

Introduction¶

  • PISA is a survey of students' skills and knowledge as they approach the end of compulsory education. It focuses on examining how well the students have learned the school curriculum and how well prepared the students are for life beyond school.

  • Around 510,000 students in 65 economies took part in the PISA 2012 assessment of reading, mathematics and science representing about 28 million 15-year-olds globally. Of those economies, 44 took part in an assessment of creative problem solving and 18 in an assessment of financial literacy.

In [6]:
# joining all columns for students grades to a single column representing the average
ds['math_grade_avg'] = (ds.PV1MATH + ds.PV2MATH + ds.PV3MATH + ds.PV4MATH + ds.PV5MATH) / 5
ds['reading_grade_avg'] = (ds.PV1READ + ds.PV2READ + ds.PV3READ + ds.PV4READ + ds.PV5READ) / 5
ds['science_grade_avg'] = (ds.PV1SCIE + ds.PV2SCIE + ds.PV3SCIE + ds.PV4SCIE + ds.PV5SCIE) / 5
In [7]:
#adding a column representing the total average grades
ds['total_avg_grade'] = ds.math_grade_avg + ds.reading_grade_avg + ds.science_grade_avg
In [8]:
#dropping the original grade columns which are now redundant
ds = ds.drop(['PV1MATH','PV2MATH','PV3MATH','PV4MATH','PV5MATH',
              'PV1READ','PV2READ','PV3READ','PV4READ','PV5READ',
            'PV1SCIE','PV2SCIE','PV3SCIE','PV4SCIE','PV5SCIE'],axis=1)

The ISCED(International Standard Classification of Education) as at 2011 had 8 levels of classification ranging from primary education to a doctorate or equivalent. The values will be re-written based on the classification levels.¶

In [17]:
#fixing the 'father' columns
ds.education_level_father = ds.education_level_father.replace('ISCED 1','primary')
ds.education_level_father = ds.education_level_father.replace('ISCED 2','lower secondary')
ds.education_level_father = ds.education_level_father.replace('ISCED 3B, C','upper secondary')
ds.education_level_father = ds.education_level_father.replace('ISCED 3A, ISCED 4','post-secondary, non-tertiary')
ds.education_level_father = ds.education_level_father.replace('ISCED 5B','short-cyle tertiary')
ds.education_level_father = ds.education_level_father.replace('ISCED 5A, 6','bachelor or masters or doctorate')

Dataset Structure¶

The dataset consists of 212,297 rows and 23 columns

Main feature(s) of interest¶

The main features of the dataset are the students and the subjects of assessment - science, math and reading

Features that should support investigation into feature(s) of interest¶

I believe the variables bordering on the student grades with regards to parental influence, background and extra-curricular activities should give a great insight for analysis

Question 14¶

By how much does learning time impact academic performance?

Visualization¶

In [52]:
sb.regplot(data=pisa, x='total_avg_learning_time',y='total_avg_grade', scatter_kws={'alpha':1/20});

Observations¶

There is a weak positive correlation between the total average grade and the total average amount of minutes spent per week learning. Learning for a long period of time doesn't necessarily guarantee a high grade. However, a minimum of 200 minutes per week seems to be the requirement for a good academic performance

Discussing the relationships observed¶

  • Straight off the bat in comparing students' grades, the students seem to be all-rounders with positive correlations between all the subjects.
  • Whether Female or Male, native or Foreign, there was a high level of academic performance being produced by the students.
  • It seemed nothing could distinguish the academic performance of the students till the parental influence was explored, students' whose parents had attained high academic degrees tend to perform better than those who did not.
  • Most of the countries can be proud of their students' performances with Hong Kong-China the standout country but with a narrow margin.
  • The amount of students in a class did not have an effect on their academic performance.
  • A minimum of 200 minutes per week in the classroom seems to be the yardstick for a good academic performance, extended periods of learning do not seem to increase academic performance.

Relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)¶

  • I noticed that the parents had very similar degrees, academically sound fathers tend to marry academically sound mothers and vice-versa.
  • Also, parents who have higher educational degrees produce more academically sound children except for when they either do not complete tertiary education or pursue something different after secondary education.

Question 16¶

Relationship between immigration status and parents' education?

Visualization¶

plt.xticks(rotation=15);

Observations¶

From both plots it can be deduced that second-generation students tend to perform better when their parents do not have a degree, while native students are positively impacted by their parents' degree acquisition.

Discussing the relationships observed¶

  • It seems students who aren't natives and whose parents do not have a degree are extra-motivated to perform better academically, while students who are natives and their parents have degrees have enough resources to out-perform their mates.
  • I initially presumed longer hours in the classroom will aid academic performance but the results show that extra hours in the classroom do not necessarily aid higher grades.

Conclusions¶

  • There was a high-level of performance among the students with differences in grades being minimal
  • The assessment was not gender-biased and nothing could split male and female students in terms of academic performance
  • Parental influence was strong, as those with degrees groomed students who performed better academically. Although, non-natives whose parents had no degrees were also high-achievers.
  • Number of students in a class did not affect academic performance
  • Longer hours of learning did not equate better academic performance
